export const POST_RAW: Record<string, string> = {
  "douglas-homes/2024-11-10-a-tale-of-red-flags-and-transparency": "---\ntitle: \"Douglas Homes Calgary Review: A Tale of Red Flags and Transparency\"\ndate: 2024-11-10T12:00:00-07:00\ndescription: \"An honest review of my experience with Douglas Homes in Calgary. Learn about the red flags I encountered and the importance of transparency when choosing a new home builder.\"\ntags: [douglas-homes-calgary, douglas-homes-reviews, new-home-builder-calgary, home-builder-complaints, new-home-warranty-alberta]\ndraft: false\nbuilder: douglas-homes\n---\n\nI want to share the story of my first attempt at buying a new home in Calgary. The builder was Douglas Homes, and the experience taught me hard lessons about transparency and due diligence.\n\nThe property was a spec home at **204 Langwell Common SE**, located in **Lanark Landing** — a community developed by **Melcor** in Airdrie, Alberta. The lot was Phase 4, Block 13, Lot 1. My salesperson was **Trish Braun**.\n\nOn November 12, 2024, I met with Trish, confirmed my initial **$5,000 bank draft** deposit was received, and signed the purchase agreement. The remaining balance of the 10% deposit was due ten business days from the contract date, after conditions were waived. At the time, I felt optimistic. That didn't last.\n\n**Red Flag #1: No sample contract, no warranty.**\n\nBefore signing, I had asked to review a sample purchase contract. Douglas Homes refused. Then, after signing, Trish stated that **Schedule C (Home Warranty) was not currently attached** and that I wasn't entitled to view it until closing. Being asked to commit to a legally binding agreement without seeing the home warranty was like boarding a plane without knowing the safety protocols.\n\n**Red Flag #2: HOA misrepresentations.**\n\nDuring our November 12 meeting, Trish assured me there were no restrictions on security cameras — any issues would fall under city bylaws. She confirmed no restrictions on fire pits unless there was a fire ban. She said the fence height restriction was the primary HOA concern, and there was nothing else I needed to be aware of. Colton noted in a contemporaneous recording (Nov 20, 2024) that Trish had told him \"the restricted cabinet for the HOA dissolves when I purchase the property\" — a claim that is factually incorrect under Melcor's continuing architectural control guidelines. {/* R2-Q3: Colton's on-record account, Nov 20 2024 DocuSign recording */} These assurances would prove to be incomplete at best.\n\n**Red Flag #3: My name was wrong on legal documents.**\n\nTrish repeatedly misspelled my name on the legal documents and refused to correct it. When I pressed the issue, I was told that changing my name on the documents now would be \"extra work\" and that they would handle it with a future change request — presumably at additional cost. On a $600,000+ purchase. My name.\n\n**Red Flag #4: DocuSign from a personal email.**\n\nThe emails and documents came from a personal email address, not a Douglas Homes corporate account. The contract was e-signed by \"DW\" through a numbered Alberta corporation's DocuSign — not Douglas Homes' own system. This raised immediate questions about the legitimacy and security of the transaction.\n\n**Red Flag #5: The bathtub specification.**\n\nMy Schedule A specified a **[Fiberglass Hytec AC759-O](https://www.hytec.ca/product-detail/AC759?skuid=AC759-0)** bathtub. After reviewing the specs, its near-full-height dimensions were a critical requirement for me. Colton later described in a recorded account how Trish counted tiles on the blueprint rather than consulting the Hytec spec sheet, concluding the tub was \"seven feet.\" {/* R2-Q2: Colton's on-record account, Nov 20 2024 DocuSign recording */} This detail would become important as the deal unravelled.\n\n**Red Flag #6: The 8-inch plot plan discrepancy.**\n\nThe most critical issue was that the spec home was built **eight inches narrower** than permitted by the architectural guidelines of Lanark Landing. The discrepancy fell under **Section 3.2.2** of the guidelines, which specified minimum lot widths. I asked Douglas Homes to contact **E2 and Associates**, the architectural committee for Lanark Landing, to obtain a formal waiver as defined by **Section 10** of the guidelines. They refused.\n\n**Upgrades we discussed.**\n\nDuring the November 12 meeting, we also discussed upgrades: tile in the walk-in closet (around **$720**), a gas line to the back of the house for approximately **$300** placed as close to the end of the deck as allowed, and Cat 6 runs in the flex room, above the fireplace, in the primary bedroom, and two in the basement bedrooms. The appliance package included an electric stove — a gas line was not available except for the furnace. The basement ceiling height was eight feet.\n\n**The collapse.**\n\nOver eight days — from signing on November 12 to the final call on November 18 — every conversation raised new concerns rather than resolving old ones. By November 20, the deal was dead. My deposit was refunded.\n\nLooking back, I wish I had applied more rigorous due diligence from the start. I wish I had demanded the home warranty and a sample contract before ever putting money down. My earnest appeal to anyone reading this: seek transparency and demand answers. Do not sweep red flags under the rug.\n\n— Colton English\n",
  "douglas-homes/2024-11-18-the-8-inch-divide": "---\ntitle: \"Douglas Homes Review: The 8-Inch Divide That Ended My Home Purchase\"\ndate: 2024-11-18T14:41:00-07:00\ndescription: \"A detailed account of my experience with Douglas Homes in Calgary, focusing on a plot plan dispute that led to the cancellation of my contract. A must-read for anyone considering building with Douglas Homes.\"\ntags: [douglas-homes-calgary, douglas-homes-reviews, new-home-builder-calgary, home-builder-complaints, new-home-warranty-alberta, plot-plan-dispute]\ndraft: false\nbuilder: douglas-homes\n---\n\nI've always believed that buying a home should be one of life's most exciting milestones. When I signed with Douglas Homes on November 12, 2024 for a spec home at **204 Langwell Common SE** in **Lanark Landing** (a Melcor community in Airdrie), I was filled with that optimism. But what unfolded over the next eight days was a cautionary tale about how even the smallest details, when overlooked or mishandled, can unravel everything.\n\nI put down a **$5,000 bank draft** as my initial deposit. My contact was **Trish Braun**. Her confidence was comforting at first, but that comfort was short-lived.\n\n**The contract and the warranty wall.**\n\nThe first crack appeared when I requested a sample purchase contract before signing. I was met with resistance — a reluctance to share details upfront. After signing, Trish told me that Schedule C (Home Warranty) was not attached and that I wasn't entitled to view it until closing. For someone who values clear communication, this was deeply unsettling.\n\n**The 8-inch discrepancy.**\n\n{/* R1-Q2: Contract recording, Nov 12 2024, lines 1187-1214 and 1822-1829 */}\n\nThe issue that shattered the deal was an eight-inch discrepancy between the architectural guidelines and the as-built dimensions of the home. The spec home was built eight inches narrower than permitted under **Section 3.2.2** of the Lanark Landing architectural guidelines, which specified minimum building widths for the lot size.\n\nAt the November 12 contract-signing meeting, Colton raised this directly. \"All the other Ferny 3s are 20 feet wide,\" he said. Trish replied: \"I have no idea… it could be a typo for all I know.\" Colton confirmed the practical impact: the missing width eliminated what \"was supposed to be a second linen closet.\" (R1-Q2, Contract recording, Nov 12, 2024)\n\nEight inches sounds trivial. In homebuilding, where precision defines property boundaries and future modifications, it was a significant deviation.\n\nI pushed hard for a formal waiver. On November 18, I made four calls:\n\n1. **To Trish Braun** — requesting that Douglas Homes pursue a waiver. She refused and said the approval stamp on the plans meant the builder was responsible for ensuring compliance, but that head office wouldn't provide further documentation.[^1]\n\n2. **To Erin at Melcor** — to understand the waiver process. I pointed out that the approval stamp stated the builder was responsible for ensuring the building aligned with all covenants, and that what Douglas Homes was asking for wasn't a waiver as defined by **Section 10** of the architectural guidelines.[^2]\n\n3. **To E2 and Associates** — the architectural committee for Lanark Landing. I explained that the spec home was built eight inches narrower than permitted by the guidelines, and that Douglas Homes didn't want to contact E2 to resolve the issue. The ideal solution would be for Douglas Homes to obtain a waiver for the discrepancy as outlined in Section 10.[^3]\n\n4. **Final call with Trish** — In this call, Trish reiterated that head office wouldn't provide further documentation and that my options were to proceed with the purchase or accept a refund of my deposit.[^4]\n\n**Other troubling signs.**\n\nAlong the way, I discovered misrepresentations about HOA rules and restrictive covenants that were never fully disclosed. The DocuSign came from a personal email address through a numbered Alberta corporation — not Douglas Homes' official system. My legal name was misspelled on the contract, and correcting it was treated as \"extra work.\"\n\n**The collapse.**\n\nAfter the final conversation on November 18, where Douglas Homes reiterated their refusal to provide any waiver or resolution, the deal collapsed on November 20. What had started as a hopeful step toward homeownership ended abruptly.\n\nThis experience taught me a hard lesson: buying a home demands transparency, respect, and clear communication. It's not about rushing into the flashiest or most convenient option — it's about ensuring your concerns are heard and addressed with honesty.\n\nTo anyone considering Douglas Homes or any builder: insist on clarity. Ask for sample contracts before you commit. Verify every detail. And demand formal resolutions to any discrepancies. Your future home deserves that level of care.\n\n— Colton English\n\n[^1]: [Recording: Final request for plot plan waiver](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1jxEC7VWIkHkLX4MQ4_CzwWFL0v8Gx3us/)\n[^2]: [Recording: Conversation with Erin at Melcor](https://drive.google.com/file/d/10ozpAVRtNaj76XGGhW6gIkzf_IioBh_l/)\n[^3]: [Recording: Call with E2 and Associates](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1fdr-DEpgIaOIMDnW5JaZTgFwaXDf04nz/)\n[^4]: [Recording: Conclusion call with Trish](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1o39GNlSlIRC_bEWFuBoFllbkfIjU1drk/)\n",
  "douglas-homes/2024-11-20-a-cautionary-tale": "---\ntitle: \"Douglas Homes Complaint: A Cautionary Tale for Calgary Home Buyers\"\ndate: 2024-11-20T17:55:00-07:00\ndescription: \"My personal experience with Douglas Homes and their salesperson, Trish Braun. This review details the issues I faced, from contract problems to a lack of professionalism, and serves as a warning to anyone considering building with this company.\"\ntags: [douglas-homes-calgary, douglas-homes-reviews, new-home-builder-calgary, home-builder-complaints, new-home-warranty-alberta, trish-braun]\ndraft: false\nbuilder: douglas-homes\n---\n\nToday, November 20, 2024, my first attempt at buying a new home officially ended. The builder was Douglas Homes. The property was **204 Langwell Common SE** in **Lanark Landing**, a Melcor community in Airdrie. The salesperson was **Trish Braun**. I want to tell you what happened, because I hope it helps you avoid the same experience.\n\n**The beginning.**\n\nI signed the purchase agreement on November 12 and put down a **$5,000 bank draft**. The home was a spec build — Phase 4, Block 13, Lot 1 of Lanark Landing. My Schedule A specified a **[Fiberglass Hytec AC759-O](https://www.hytec.ca/product-detail/AC759?skuid=AC759-0)** bathtub, whose near-full-height dimensions were a critical requirement. We discussed upgrades including tile in the walk-in closet (around **$720**), a gas line to the back of the house (approximately **$300**), Cat 6 ethernet runs on the main floor and in the basement, and an eight-foot basement ceiling height.\n\n**The red flags I ignored.**\n\nRight from the start, Trish refused to provide a sample contract before signing. After signing, she told me Schedule C (Home Warranty) was not attached and I wasn't entitled to view it until closing. Colton noted in a same-day recording that the DocuSign invitation \"goes to a random numbered Corporation.\" When he raised this with office staff, they replied: \"That's a really good question. I don't know that I have the answer.\" {/* R2-Q1: DocuSign recording, Nov 20 2024 */} The contract documents came from a personal email address, e-signed by \"DW\" through a numbered corporation's DocuSign — not Douglas Homes' own system.\n\n**Misrepresentations and the name game.**\n\nAfter signing, I discovered that the HOA rules and restrictive covenants were not what Trish had represented during our meeting. Colton noted in a contemporaneous recording (Nov 20, 2024) that Trish had told him \"the restricted cabinet for the HOA dissolves when I purchase the property\" — a claim that is factually incorrect under Melcor's continuing architectural control guidelines. {/* R2-Q3: DocuSign recording, Nov 20 2024 */} On top of that, in the same recording, Colton described a name discrepancy: \"That signature is with Colton English, the contract's with Colton Wade.\" He noted that rather than reissuing the contract, Trish suggested he \"sign it with the wrong name and then reissue.\" {/* R2-Q4: DocuSign recording, Nov 20 2024 */}\n\n**The 8-inch discrepancy.**\n\nThe deal-breaking issue was an eight-inch discrepancy between the as-built home and the minimum building width under **Section 3.2.2** of the Lanark Landing architectural guidelines. I asked Douglas Homes to obtain a formal waiver from **E2 and Associates** (the architectural committee) under **Section 10** of the guidelines. They refused.\n\n**The final call.**\n\nOn November 18, I had a final phone call with Trish. I opened the call by stating: **\"This is a recorded phone call.\"**[^1] Trish's response to the recording was straightforward — she didn't object. But her position was clear:\n\n> \"In speaking with the management group at head office, there's nothing more they can provide as it relates to this… it's up to your comfort level, if you're comfortable going ahead. Otherwise, they can certainly refund your deposit.\"\n\nAnd then:\n\n> \"There's not gonna be any more discussions about my DocuSign and the e-mail that it came from, or any more discussions on the plotting of the house on the lot. It is what it is.\"\n\n**\"It is what it is.\"** On a $600,000+ home purchase. On questions about the legitimacy of the signing process and the compliance of the plot plan. That was the answer.\n\n**Why I'm sharing this.**\n\nWhen you're trading 30 years of your life for a home, you expect a certain level of respect and professionalism. You expect to feel like a valued partner in the process, not a nuisance. My experience with Douglas Homes was the opposite. The deposit was refunded, and I moved on. But the lesson stayed: demand transparency, document everything, and never let a builder tell you that your concerns about a legal agreement are simply \"what it is.\"\n\nStay informed, stay cautious, and good luck on your home buying journey.\n\n— Colton English\n\n[^1]: [Recording: November 12 meeting with Trish](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1WPC1CKvAQ1dBWkKSnx8mIjgim5tLdb6_/)\n",
  "house/2024-11-01-introduction": "---\ntitle: \"My Journey Home: A Guide to Navigating the New Home Build Process\"\ndate: 2024-11-01T12:00:00-07:00\ndescription: \"Follow Colton English's journey through the new home build process, from first steps to final walkthrough.\"\ntags: [home-buying, introduction, lessons-learned]\ndraft: false\n---\n\nWelcome. I'm Colton English, and this is the story of my journey buying a new home.\n\nFor me, buying a house isn't just a financial transaction — it's a 30-year commitment. It's an exchange of a significant portion of my life for a place of comfort, safety, and security. This blog is my way of documenting that journey honestly: the highs and lows, the good builders and the bad ones, the contracts that fell apart and the one that finally worked.\n\nMy journey began in late 2024, without a blueprint (pun intended). All I knew was that I wanted a space of my own — one crafted to my needs, one I could look at years from now as a testament to perseverance and hard-won lessons.\n\nIn the beginning, my view of home-building was romantic. Picking paint colours, choosing fixtures, imagining how the light would fall in the living room. As I embarked on this path, that rosy vision was replaced by the gritty reality of managing contracts, navigating deposits, chasing down specifications, and learning building codes complex enough to make your head spin.\n\nYet I wouldn't trade this journey for anything. The bumps along the way — and there were many — eventually helped me navigate the new home building terrain with growing confidence. Today, as I sit in my home, I can see how each hurdle shaped my understanding of this process.\n\nIn this blog, I'll share the stages of my journey: selecting the right builder, managing your budget, dealing with contract disputes, and ultimately, taking possession of a newly built home. All with the intent of equipping you — potential new home buyers and builder researchers — with real, lived experience rather than marketing copy.\n\nI hope in reading my story you'll find solace that you're not alone in this daunting, yet ultimately rewarding, undertaking. I hope that with each post, you discover something that helps ease your worries or clear your confusion.\n\nThis blog is my journey home. I hope it provides a map for yours.\n\nSincerely,\nColton English.\n",
  "house/2025-07-26-conclusion": "---\ntitle: \"Lessons from the Journey: A Final Reflection\"\ndate: 2025-07-26T12:45:00-06:00\ndescription: \"A final reflection on the home-buying journey with key takeaways for potential buyers.\"\ntags: [home-buying, conclusion, lessons-learned]\ndraft: false\n---\n\nThis is the final post in my home-buying journey series. I'm writing this from Langley Terrace SE in Airdrie — the Sterling Homes \"Luna\" that I took possession of on June 2, 2025 — and I want to look back at the trail I traveled to get here.\n\nMy path to homeownership ran through three builders over about seven months:\n\n1. **Douglas Homes** (November 2024) — I signed a contract for a spec home at 204 Langwell Common SE in Lanark Landing, a Melcor community in Airdrie. I put down a $5,000 bank draft. Over eight days, I discovered an 8-inch plot plan discrepancy, a refusal to provide the home warranty before closing, and a salesperson who sent contracts from a personal email through a numbered corporation's DocuSign. The deal collapsed on November 20 when Douglas Homes refused to seek a formal waiver under Section 10 of the architectural guidelines and offered to refund my deposit instead.\n\n2. **Jayman Built** (March–May 2025) — I received a purchase agreement on March 4, 2025 for an Avid 20 with revised ensuite at 71 Legacy Reach Court SE in Calgary's Legacy community. I paid $7,820 for the revised ensuite and $12,600 for the Fit and Finish Extra package. Their brochure promised \"80\" height, chrome frame, 10 mil glass shower door\" — but the contract was vague, and when I asked for clarification, the specs kept shrinking: first to 70\"/5mil, then 75\"/6mil. After 16 days of silence from the sales manager and a formal dispute letter to the VP, Jayman terminated the agreement in early May.\n\n3. **Sterling Homes** (May–June 2025) — My first contact was Jason Tang, and the difference was immediate. No sales pressure, straight answers. The purchase agreement was comprehensive, every schedule was present, and the home warranty was included as a matter of course. CIBC approved my mortgage on May 21. The home inspection on May 28 with Marty Keough from Nook & Cranny came back clean. I took possession on June 2.\n\nHere's what I learned.\n\n**Lesson One: Demand the contract before you sign anything.**\n\nDouglas Homes refused to provide a sample contract or the home warranty (Schedule C) before closing. That's not standard practice — it's a red flag. If a builder won't let you review the full agreement and all schedules before you put money down, walk away.\n\n**Lesson Two: The brochure is not the contract.**\n\nJayman's glossy Fit and Finish brochure described an 80\" shower with 10mil glass. The contract referenced \"other shower stalls applicable to plan\" without specifying dimensions or materials. When there's a gap between what's advertised and what's written, the written contract governs — and builders know this. Get every specification that matters to you written into the agreement explicitly.\n\n**Lesson Three: Record everything.**\n\nI recorded phone calls (with notice), saved every email, and documented every conversation. When Douglas Homes told me to \"just trust them,\" the recordings told a different story. When Jayman's specs changed between April 10 and April 11, the emails were the evidence. Documentation isn't paranoia — it's due diligence.\n\n**Lesson Four: A quick-possession home can be the right move.**\n\nAfter two failed attempts with pre-construction homes, Sterling's quick-possession Luna model meant I could see exactly what I was buying. I was settled into my home before Jayman had even broken ground on the Legacy lot, and long before the Douglas Homes property would have been completed. The home was more affordable and included the features that mattered most to me, including full-height tile in the bathroom — the very detail that was the centre of my dispute with Jayman.\n\n**Lesson Five: The sale is just the beginning.**\n\nPost-possession brought its own challenges: a site supervisor (Mike) who dismissed concerns and provided dangerously wrong information about foam off-gassing, a warranty app (Virtuo) with a critical Android bug, and an eavestrough issue that took weeks to get addressed. The warranty phase tested my patience more than the buying phase. Be prepared to advocate for yourself after the keys are in your hand.\n\nThis journey has been about more than buying a house. It's been about understanding the value of a 30-year commitment — the exchange of time for security, and the importance of finding a builder who respects that. My hope is that by sharing this story, I can help you find a builder who will honour your commitment and help you build a home that is truly worth the exchange.\n\n— Colton English\n",
  "jayman-built/2025-03-04-a-tale-of-two-contracts": "---\ntitle: \"Jayman Built Calgary Review: The Agreement and the Discrepancy\"\ndescription: \"A personal review of my experience signing a purchase agreement with Jayman Built in Calgary, and discovering that the brochure's ensuite shower specifications were not in the contract.\"\ndate: 2025-03-04T12:00:00-07:00\ntags: [jayman-built-calgary, jayman-built-reviews, new-home-builder-calgary, home-builder-complaints, new-home-warranty-alberta, avid-ratings, trustedpros]\ndraft: false\nbuilder: jayman-built\n---\n\nAfter my experience with Douglas Homes collapsed in November 2024, I started looking again. My second attempt at buying a new home was with Jayman Built, and it began with genuine optimism.\n\n**March 4, 2025: The purchase agreement.**\n\nOn March 4, 2025, I received the purchase agreement for a home at **71 Legacy Reach Court SE, Calgary, Alberta**, in the community of **Legacy**. The model was an **Avid 20 with revised ensuite** — not the \"Cooper\" that some of their marketing referenced, but the Avid 20 specifically. My sales associate was **Brittney Mack**.\n\nThe agreement included two key line items:\n- **$7,820** for the \"Revised Ensuite\" — creating a 4-piece ensuite with a separate soaker tub and shower\n- **$12,600** for \"Fit and Finish Extra (2)\"\n\nThe contract also referenced specifications from the Jayman Built [Fit and Finish Brochure](https://www.jayman.com/assets/Uploads/JAY-2609-Fit-and-Finish-Brochure-CAL_WEB_2025.pdf), which described the ensuite in specific, enticing terms:\n\n> \"4-piece ensuites include curbless tiled shower recessed into the floor sloped towards a 32\" linear drain. Walls are tiled to ceiling. Includes 80\" height, chrome frame, 10 mil glass shower door.\"\n\nThis brochure wasn't a vague marketing flyer — it read like a specification sheet. The shower it described was a significant part of why I chose this home. The floor plan showed a marked 42\" by 48\" ensuite shower in the 4-piece configuration.\n\n**The gap between the brochure and the contract.**\n\nWhen I read the contract closely, the ensuite shower specification was vague. The luxurious details from the brochure — the 80\" height, the 10mil glass, the chrome frame — were nowhere in the written agreement. The contract's only reference to the shower was a clause about \"other shower stalls applicable to plan,\" taken from Addendum B, page 4, point 3. No dimensions. No materials. No specifics.\n\nI raised this with Brittney, hoping it was a simple oversight. It wasn't.\n\n**Mid-April: The specs start shrinking.**\n\nOn April 10, 2025, Brittney emailed me with what she said the actual specification would be: a **70\" height with 5mil glass**. When I challenged this — pointing to the brochure's explicit 80\"/10mil promise — the spec was revised on April 11 to **75\" height with 6mil glass**. Still not what the brochure promised. And none of these numbers appeared anywhere in the signed contract or its addenda.\n\nMeanwhile, Jayman insisted that upgrading to the 80\" height and 10mil glass promised in the brochure was a nearly **$7,000 CAD upgrade**. The brochure had described it as a standard feature. The contract was silent on it. And now they wanted $7,000 to deliver what was advertised.\n\n**The silence.**\n\nOn April 11, I requested escalation to the sales manager, **Michael Klassen**. Despite multiple follow-up emails on April 16, April 17, and April 26, no contact was initiated by Mr. Klassen. It took a direct email from me on **April 27** — explicitly stating concern over the good faith nature of the 16-day delay — to finally elicit a response later that same day.\n\nOn **April 28, 2025**, I sent a formal dispute letter to **Stephanie Myers**, Vice President of Jayman Built Single Family in Calgary, with copies to **David Hooge** (COO) and **Jay Westman** (Chairman & CEO). The letter laid out the discrepancy, cited the brochure specifications verbatim, and requested remediation including confirmation of a **Navien NPE 240A tankless water heater** as specified in Addendum B.\n\nUnder the principle of *contra proferentem* — that ambiguous contract terms should be interpreted against the party that drafted them — I believed my interpretation was reasonable and legally defensible.\n\n**The end.**\n\nIn early May, Jayman Built terminated the purchase agreement. The home I had planned at Legacy Reach Court was gone.\n\nThis experience taught me that a brochure is not a contract, and that when a builder leaves the contract intentionally vague, the gap between what's advertised and what's delivered can be enormous. If a specification matters to you, demand it in writing — in the contract itself, not in a glossy PDF.\n\n— Colton English\n",
  "jayman-built/2025-04-28-the-shower-and-the-silence": "---\ntitle: \"The Shower and the Silence: A Story of Unmet Expectations\"\ndescription: \"A detailed account of a dispute with Jayman Built over misleading brochure specifications and vague contract language for an ensuite shower, and the communication failures that followed.\"\ndate: 2025-04-28T15:29:08-06:00\ntags: [jayman-built, home-buying, contracts, transparency, lessons-learned, dispute]\ndraft: false\nbuilder: jayman-built\n---\n\nMy experience with Jayman Built came down to a shower — and the silence that followed when I asked them to deliver what they advertised.\n\nI chose Jayman Built for a home at **71 Legacy Reach Court SE** in Calgary's **Legacy** community. The model was an **Avid 20 with revised ensuite**. The purchase agreement arrived on **March 4, 2025**. I paid **$7,820** for the \"Revised Ensuite\" creating a 4-piece ensuite, and **$12,600** for \"Fit and Finish Extra (2).\"\n\nAmong the features that drew me in, one stood out: the ensuite shower described in Jayman's [Fit and Finish Brochure](https://www.jayman.com/assets/Uploads/JAY-2609-Fit-and-Finish-Brochure-CAL_WEB_2025.pdf):\n\n> \"4-piece ensuites include curbless tiled shower recessed into the floor sloped towards a 32\" linear drain. Walls are tiled to ceiling. Includes 80\" height, chrome frame, 10 mil glass shower door.\"\n\nThis wasn't a vague marketing promise. It read like a specification. The floor plan showed a 42\" by 48\" shower base. This was a significant part of why I chose this home.\n\n**The contract was silent.**\n\nWhen the contract landed, that specification was nowhere. The only reference to the shower was Addendum B, page 4, point 3: \"other shower stalls applicable to plan.\" No dimensions, no materials, no glass thickness. The brochure was referenced as \"the brochure\" without disclaimers. The ambiguity was a glaring red flag.\n\n**The specs kept shrinking.**\n\nI reached out to my sales associate, **Brittney Mack**, to clarify. On **April 10**, Brittney emailed that the specification would be **70\" height with 5mil glass**. When I challenged this against the brochure's explicit 80\"/10mil, she revised it on **April 11** to **75\" height with 6mil glass**. Still not what was advertised. And none of these specs were documented in the signed contract or its addenda.\n\nWhen I cited the brochure, Brittney referenced Addendum B, page 4, point 3 — \"other shower stalls applicable to plan\" — but failed to point to any specific clause or document defining the dimensions or materials.\n\nJayman insisted that upgrading to the 80\" height and 10mil glass described in their own brochure was a nearly **$7,000 CAD upgrade**. The brochure described it as standard. The contract was silent. And now they wanted $7,000 to deliver what was advertised.\n\n**The 16-day silence.**\n\nOn April 11, I requested escalation to the sales manager, **Michael Klassen**. Despite multiple email follow-ups on **April 16, April 17, and April 26**, no contact was initiated. It took a direct email from me to Mr. Klassen on **April 27**, explicitly stating concern over the good faith nature of the **16-day delay**, to finally elicit a response later that same day.\n\n**The formal dispute.**\n\nOn **April 28, 2025**, I sent a formal dispute letter to **Stephanie Myers**, Vice President of Jayman Built Single Family in Calgary, with copies to **David Hooge** (COO) and **Jay Westman** (Chairman & CEO).\n\nThe letter requested specific remediations including:\n- Shower dimensions: 42\" x 48\" base, 80\" height from threshold, 10mil clear glass, chrome frame, 8\" D handle\n- Written confirmation, via contract amendment, that the home would include the **Navien NPE 240A tankless water heater** as specified in Addendum B, Page 4\n\nI cited the principle of ***contra proferentem*** — that ambiguous contract terms should be interpreted against the party that drafted them. My interpretation was reasonable and legally defensible.\n\n**The termination.**\n\nIn early May, Jayman Built terminated the purchase agreement. The home at Legacy Reach Court was gone.\n\nThis story is not just about a shower. It's about the gap between what's advertised and what's delivered, and the silence that fills that gap when you ask for accountability. Jayman's brochure was the bait. The vague contract was the trap. And when I pushed back, the response was weeks of silence followed by termination.\n\nTo anyone considering Jayman Built: look beyond the brochure. Get every specification that matters to you written into the contract itself. Watch for vague language. And if you encounter silence when seeking answers, take it as the answer it is.\n\n— Colton English\n",
  "sterling-homes/2025-05-03-a-new-beginning": "---\ntitle: \"Sterling Homes Calgary Review: A New Beginning\"\ndescription: \"A personal review of my experience with Sterling Homes in Calgary. This post details the positive and collaborative relationship I had with this new home builder, and how it restored my faith in the home-buying process.\"\ndate: 2025-05-03T01:00:00-06:00\ntags: [sterling-homes-calgary, sterling-homes-reviews, new-home-builder-calgary, avid-ratings, home-awards, new-home-warranty-alberta]\ndraft: false\nbuilder: sterling-homes\n---\n\nAfter two failed attempts at buying a new home — Douglas Homes in November 2024 and Jayman Built from March to May 2025 — I was running low on optimism. Then I found Sterling Homes, and the difference was immediate.\n\n**The first meeting.**\n\nMy first point of contact was **Jason Tang** (lanark@sterlingcalgary.com), and there was no sales pressure, no vague hand-waving — just straight answers. After my experience with a salesperson who sent contracts from a personal email and a builder whose brochure specs didn't match the contract, Jason's directness was a relief.\n\nThe home was a **quick-possession \"Luna\" model** at **Langley Terrace SE, Airdrie, AB** (job number J#158004). A quick-possession home meant I could see exactly what I was buying — no more speculation about what \"applicable to plan\" might mean.\n\n**The contract.**\n\nThe purchase agreement (`158004_-_Sterling_Homes_Purchase_Agreementpd.pdf`) was comprehensive and clear. Every schedule was present, every specification was detailed, and there were no glaring omissions or ambiguous clauses. The home warranty — a document I had to fight to even see with Douglas Homes — was included as a matter of course.\n\n**Why it mattered.**\n\nThe home at Langley Terrace was more affordable than the property I had considered in Legacy with Jayman. But the benefits didn't stop at the price tag. I was able to get the features that were most important to me, including a full-height tile bathroom — a detail that had been the centre of my dispute with Jayman — and a front garage.\n\nThe quick-possession timeline was a major advantage. I would be settled into my new house before Jayman had even broken ground on the Legacy lot, and long before the Douglas Homes property at 204 Langwell Common SE would have been completed.\n\n**Not perfect, but honest.**\n\nI don't want to paint Sterling Homes as flawless. The post-possession experience would bring its own challenges — a site supervisor whose interpersonal skills didn't match his construction knowledge, a warranty app with critical bugs, and repairs that tested my patience. I'll cover all of that in later posts.\n\nBut the sales process — the part that had gone so badly wrong twice before — was transparent, efficient, and respectful. After months of red flags and broken promises, Sterling Homes felt like a genuine partner in the process rather than an adversary.\n\nFor the first time in my home-buying journey, I felt confident I had made the right choice.\n\n— Colton English\n",
  "sterling-homes/2025-06-02-the-unveiled-reality-of-homeownership": "---\ntitle: \"Sterling Homes Calgary Review: The Unveiled Reality of Homeownership\"\ndescription: \"A detailed account of my post-possession experience with Sterling Homes in Calgary. This review covers the mortgage, inspection, possession day, and the challenges that followed.\"\ndate: 2025-06-02T01:00:00-06:00\ntags: [sterling-homes-calgary, sterling-homes-reviews, new-home-builder-calgary, home-builder-complaints, new-home-warranty-alberta, virtuo-app]\ndraft: false\nbuilder: sterling-homes\n---\n\nThe journey from signing the purchase agreement to holding the keys was remarkably smooth. It was everything that came after that tested me.\n\n**Mortgage: May 21, 2025.**\n\nI was working with two lenders, ATB and CIBC, to ensure I was getting the best possible terms. **Jason Tang** was a model of efficiency — he was in constant communication with my mortgage advisor at CIBC, **Heather Hannah**. On **May 21, 2025**, I received the official approval letter from CIBC. After the contract chaos with Douglas Homes and the specification disputes with Jayman, having the financing locked down felt like crossing a real finish line.\n\n**Home inspection: May 28, 2025.**\n\nI hired **Marty Keough** from **Nook & Cranny Home Inspections**, a firm with a reputation for thoroughness. The inspection of **Langley Terrace**, conducted on **May 28, 2025**, came back remarkably clean. The list of deficiencies was short and consisted of minor, cosmetic issues that were easily addressed. There were no major structural problems, no plumbing or electrical issues, and no signs of shoddy workmanship.\n\n**Possession day: June 2, 2025.**\n\nJune 2, 2025 was possession day. I met **Mike**, the site supervisor, for the walkthrough. At first glance, Mike seemed competent and helpful. The walkthrough itself went smoothly enough. But this was the calm before the storm.\n\n**The first cracks.**\n\nOn possession day itself, two incidents set the tone for what was to come.\n\nFirst, I noticed that the doors on the stacking washer and dryer were hinged on opposite sides, making it awkward to move clothes from one to the other. When I pointed this out and asked if it could be fixed, as I noted in my post-possession records, Mike's response was to tell me I was wrong for thinking the doors should align. It was an unnecessarily defensive reaction to a simple observation.\n\nSecond — and more seriously — one of the outstanding items on the possession list was the foam insulation for the basement party wall. As I noted in my post-possession records, Mike assured me this would be quick: \"It'll only take about half an hour.\" When the crew arrived, they told me the foam would **off-gas for approximately 24 hours** and that it would be **unsafe to stay in the house during that time**. On possession day. The day I was supposed to move in. I consider Mike's \"half an hour\" estimate not just wrong — but dangerously misleading.\n\n**What's ahead.**\n\nThe sales process with Sterling was the best of my three builder experiences. Jason Tang, Heather Hannah, and Marty Keough all did their jobs with professionalism and competence. But the post-possession phase — the warranty claims, the Virtuo app, the ongoing repairs, and Mike — would be a different story entirely.\n\nBecoming a homeowner is a milestone and a journey. The path from contract to keys was smooth. The path from keys to \"this actually feels like home\" is the harder one.\n\n— Colton English\n",
  "sterling-homes/2025-06-15-something-about-mike": "---\ntitle: \"Something About Mike: A Candid Review\"\ndescription: \"A candid review of site supervisor Mike's pattern of dismissiveness and a dangerous safety incident during the Sterling Homes possession process.\"\ndate: 2025-06-15T01:00:00-06:00\ntags: [sterling-homes, home-buying, customer-service, transparency, lessons-learned]\ndraft: false\nbuilder: sterling-homes\n---\n\nMike was the site supervisor for my Sterling Homes property at Langley Terrace. His construction knowledge was solid. His interpersonal skills were another story. As I documented in my post-possession notes, a pattern emerged over my first weeks as a homeowner: Mike dismissed concerns, overrode colleagues, and — in one case — provided dangerously wrong safety information.\n\n**Incident 1: The dryer door.**\n\nOn possession day, June 2, 2025, I noticed that the doors on the stacking washer and dryer were hinged on opposite sides, making it awkward to transfer clothes between them. I pointed this out and asked if it could be fixed before moving in. As I noted in my post-possession records, instead of acknowledging the inconvenience or simply explaining that it wasn't possible, Mike's response was to tell me I was wrong for thinking the doors should align. I found this to be a bizarre and unnecessarily defensive reaction to a straightforward observation.\n\n**Incident 2: The foam off-gassing (safety incident).**\n\nThis one is serious. One of the outstanding items on the possession list was the foam insulation for the basement party wall. This was supposed to be completed before I moved in, but it was delayed until possession day.\n\nAs I noted in my post-possession records, Mike assured me it would be quick and painless. **\"It'll only take about half an hour,\"** he said.\n\nWhen the spray foam crew arrived, they told me the foam would **off-gas for approximately 24 hours** and that it would be **unsafe to stay in the house during that time**. On possession day. The day I had scheduled my move.\n\nI consider Mike's \"half an hour\" estimate a safety concern. If I had relied on his assurance and stayed in the house, I would have been exposed to toxic off-gassing fumes. The crew's 24-hour warning directly contradicted Mike's casual dismissal.\n\n**Incident 3: Dismissing a colleague.**\n\nDuring the walkthrough, **Yaz** — a colleague who was consistently professional and helpful — pointed out a dark spot on the ceiling, a clear, visible water stain. As I observed during the walkthrough, before she could even finish her sentence, Mike talked over her, dismissing it as a shadow or a trick of the light. Yaz was doing her job. From what I witnessed, Mike's instinct was to shut her down rather than investigate.\n\n**Incident 4: The cracked plastic.**\n\nA few days after possession, I discovered a small, 3mm piece of cracked plastic on one of the new appliances. The broken piece had been carefully set back in place — which I interpreted as an attempt to hide the defect. As I noted in my post-possession records, when I pointed this out to Mike, his response was not an apology or an offer to replace it, but a shrug.\n\n**The pattern.**\n\nEach incident on its own might seem minor. Together, as documented in my post-possession notes, they reveal a pattern: dismissal of valid concerns, overriding of colleagues, and a default to \"you're wrong\" rather than \"let me look into it.\" I consider the foam off-gassing incident as crossing from frustrating into genuinely dangerous territory.\n\nWhen you're making a 30-year commitment, you expect the people you're working with to take it as seriously as you do. As I documented in my post-possession notes, Mike's construction knowledge may be solid, but his dismissive attitude and the dangerously inaccurate safety information about the foam off-gassing made the early days of homeownership far more stressful than they needed to be.\n\n— Colton English\n",
  "sterling-homes/2025-06-20-unfiltered-feedback": "---\ntitle: \"My Unfiltered Feedback to Sterling Homes\"\ndescription: \"Unfiltered feedback on the Sterling Homes experience, covering issues with dismissive communication, the dysfunctional Virtuo app, and eavestrough warranty issues.\"\ndate: 2025-06-20T01:00:00-06:00\ntags: [sterling-homes, home-buying, customer-service, transparency, lessons-learned, virtuo]\ndraft: false\nbuilder: sterling-homes\n---\n\nI want to share some unfiltered feedback about my experience with Sterling Homes. I acknowledge upfront that I've had positive experiences with several members of the team. But the overall post-possession experience has left enough of a bitter taste that I need to lay it all out.\n\n**Mike.**\n\nI've written about Mike separately, but to summarize: as I documented in my post-possession notes, the site supervisor was dismissive and unprofessional. When I raised a concern about the washer and dryer door alignment, Mike dismissed it outright rather than acknowledging the issue. I observed Mike talk over his colleague **Yaz** when she pointed out a visible water stain on the ceiling. As I noted in my post-possession records, Mike provided dangerously wrong information about foam off-gassing on possession day — telling me it would take \"half an hour\" when the crew said **24 hours and that it was unsafe to stay**. A 3mm piece of cracked plastic on an appliance had been carefully set back in place — which I interpreted as an attempt to hide the defect. Mike shrugged it off.\n\n**The Virtuo app.**\n\nSterling uses an app called **Virtuo** for warranty support and communication. As a tech-savvy person, I was initially excited about this. The reality was different.\n\nThe app had a critical UI bug on my **Google Pixel** phone: the navigation menu rendered *underneath* the native Android navigation buttons, making it physically impossible to tap the \"task\" icon. This isn't an edge case — Google's Pixel phones have a significant market share. It made core functionality unusable.\n\nBeyond the bug, the \"Virtuo agents\" on the other end simply never actioned my requests. Days, and then weeks, would go by with no response, no acknowledgement, and no progress. Support inquiries were ignored, tickets were left unresolved for extended periods.\n\n**The eavestrough.**\n\nMy initial concerns about the eavestrough were raised on **June 30, 2025**, when I reported improperly sloped gutters leading to persistent pooling of water on the southwest corner.\n\nOn **July 11**, I expressed my frustration to **Jaspreet Gill**, noting a **90-degree joint** that did not appear to be properly cut and jointed, and the potential impact of the poor eavestrough installation with water escaping.\n\n**Don Allary** from **Empire Envelope** — the subcontractor — sent a terse reply: *\"We have fix the drainage issue with the eavestrough.\"* The issue was far from resolved, but that was the extent of the response.\n\n**The outsourcing problem.**\n\nSterling outsources portions of their customer service to third-party agencies. The level of intimacy and comfort you naturally expect from direct communication with the builder is lost when interactions are facilitated by an impersonal third party. This outsourcing disrupted the flow of communication and seriously impacted the quality of the post-possession experience.\n\n**Credit where it's due.**\n\nSeveral other Sterling staff members were transparent and forthcoming. Transparency and honesty are core values of mine, and I appreciated those who embodied them. But the negative aspects — what I experienced as Mike's dismissiveness, the dysfunctional Virtuo app, the eavestrough runaround, and the outsourced customer service — seriously overshadowed those positive moments.\n\nI hope this feedback serves as a candid wake-up call for Sterling Homes. They have potential and resources, but unless they address these gaps in customer service and professionalism, they risk alienating more homeowners.\n\n— Colton English\n",
  "sterling-homes/2025-07-12-warranty-and-repair-review": "---\ntitle: \"The State of the House: A Sterling Homes Warranty and Repair Review\"\ndescription: \"A comprehensive review of the Sterling Homes warranty and repair experience, covering every warranty item, the warranty team, and lessons for new home buyers.\"\ndate: 2025-07-12T20:06:51-06:00\ntags: [sterling-homes, home-buying, customer-service, transparency, lessons-learned, warranty, repair]\ndraft: false\nbuilder: sterling-homes\n---\n\nI took possession of my Sterling Homes property at **Langley Terrace SE, Airdrie, AB** on **June 2, 2025**. My one-year builder's warranty expires on **June 2, 2026**. This post is a comprehensive accounting of every warranty and repair item I've dealt with — the good, the bad, and the still-outstanding.\n\n## The Warranty Team\n\nOver the past year, I've interacted with the following people on the Sterling Homes warranty side:\n\n| Person | Role |\n|---|---|\n| **Aly Derwent** | Customer Response Lead (warranty@sterlingcalgary.com) |\n| **Adam Pocock** | Customer Relations Coordinator (adam.pocock@sterlingcalgary.com) |\n| **Deborah Curran** | Warranty Response Representative (deborah.curran@sterlingcalgary.com) |\n| **Brendan McElroy** | Warranty Technical Lead (brendan.mcelroy@sterlingcalgary.com) |\n| **Nick Mintchev** | Warranty Tech (nmintchev@sterlingcalgary.com) |\n\nCredit where it's due: the warranty team has generally been responsive and organized, even when the underlying issues were slow to resolve. The contrast with what I experienced as a dismissive site supervisor (Mike) during the possession phase is stark.\n\n## Warranty Items — Chronological\n\n### Eavestrough (June 30, 2025 → July 11 → ongoing)\nReported improperly sloped eavestroughs leading to persistent pooling of water on the southwest corner on **June 30**. On **July 11**, I flagged a **90-degree joint** that was not properly cut and jointed to **Jaspreet Gill**. **Don Allary** from **Empire Envelope** claimed the drainage issue was fixed. It wasn't. This item remained open and I later sent an email titled \"Urgent: Unresolved Eavestrough Deficiencies.\"\n\n### Stairwell Window (July 15, 2025)\nThe stairwell window glass was cracked. **Aly Derwent** confirmed the window was scheduled for replacement on **July 15, 2025**.\n\n### Driveway and Walkway (July 24, 2025)\n**July 24, 2025** marked a significant milestone: the concrete for the driveway and walkway was finally poured. A Virtuo email from July 15 had noted seasonal delays due to heavy rain. Drive/walkway final grading was also tracked as a separate item.\n\n### Fireplace — Missing Crystals and Not Turning On (August 7, 2025)\nThe fireplace was missing its decorative crystals and wouldn't turn on. Aly Derwent confirmed they were waiting on a part for the fireplace repair. An appointment with **Enercare** was scheduled for **August 7, 2025**.\n\n### Ceiling Texture Repair — Kitchen (August 18–21, 2025)\nA ceiling texture repair was needed in the kitchen area, anticipated to be scheduled between **August 18 and August 21, 2025**. This item was also noted on the inspection sheet (`158004 - First inspection - Langley Terrace.xlsx`).\n\n### Dryer Door (Possession Day)\nThe dryer door was reversed. As I noted in my post-possession records, Mike was dismissive about it, insisting it was supposed to be that way. Tracked in the Notion database.\n\n### Foam Basement Party Wall (Possession Day)\nFoam insulation for the basement party wall was delayed until possession day. As I noted in my post-possession records, Mike claimed it would take 30 minutes. The crew said 24 hours of off-gassing, unsafe to stay. I consider this a safety incident on day one.\n\n### Additional Tracked Items\n- **Batten paint** — Open. Complete all batten painting.\n- **Roof final and cleaning** — Deborah Curran forwarded to Jaspreet for review.\n- **Loose soffit after high winds** — Sterling Warranty acknowledged; piece appeared to have no screws.\n- **Front sod** — Pending.\n- **Front steps to be topped up** — Pending.\n- **Parging** — Pending.\n- **Seasonal topsoil** — Pending.\n- **Texturing repair in hallway** — Pending.\n- **Illegal dumping / construction waste** — Construction waste from the site across the street was blowing into the yard.\n\n## Hot Water Failure (December 2025 → ongoing)\n\nIn **late December 2025**, the hot water failed. A vendor (Lynx Plumbing) reached out in late January/early February 2026.\n\n**Brendan McElroy** noted: \"In order for us to review the issue, we may need to cut some drywall to inspect the water lines and insulation. The water lines are covered with the 2-year distribution warranty.\"\n\n**Adam Pocock** confirmed: \"Lynx Plumbing will attend your upcoming year-end inspection to locate and address the cause of the problem.\"\n\n## Year-End Inspection\n\nOn **April 1, 2026**, **Deborah Curran** emailed: \"Your one-year builder's warranty with Sterling Homes concludes on June 2nd.\" She offered a year-end inspection: **\"Would May 26th @ 9:00am work for you for Nick to come over?\"**\n\nThe year-end inspection on **May 26, 2026** will include **Nick Mintchev** and the Lynx Plumbing investigation into the hot water issue. The warranty expires on **June 2, 2026**.\n\n## The Big Picture\n\nThe initial purchase was smooth — much of this was down to Sterling's excellent communication on financing, concierge services, and possession documents. The construction quality was generally good, and the seasonal work (driveway, grading, landscaping) has improved the curb appeal significantly.\n\nThe warranty phase, though, has been a test of patience. Between the Virtuo app's dysfunction, the eavestrough runaround, the fireplace delay, and the hot water failure, staying on top of every item has been a part-time job. Keep records. Document everything. And don't let survey fatigue stop you from flagging issues.\n\nHere's to making houses into homes.\n\n— Colton English\n",
};

export const POST_HTML: Record<string, string> = {
  "douglas-homes/2024-11-10-a-tale-of-red-flags-and-transparency": "<p>I want to share the story of my first attempt at buying a new home in Calgary. The builder was Douglas Homes, and the experience taught me hard lessons about transparency and due diligence.</p>\n<p>The property was a spec home at <strong>204 Langwell Common SE</strong>, located in <strong>Lanark Landing</strong> — a community developed by <strong>Melcor</strong> in Airdrie, Alberta. The lot was Phase 4, Block 13, Lot 1. My salesperson was <strong>Trish Braun</strong>.</p>\n<p>On November 12, 2024, I met with Trish, confirmed my initial <strong>$5,000 bank draft</strong> deposit was received, and signed the purchase agreement. The remaining balance of the 10% deposit was due ten business days from the contract date, after conditions were waived. At the time, I felt optimistic. That didn't last.</p>\n<p><strong>Red Flag #1: No sample contract, no warranty.</strong></p>\n<p>Before signing, I had asked to review a sample purchase contract. Douglas Homes refused. Then, after signing, Trish stated that <strong>Schedule C (Home Warranty) was not currently attached</strong> and that I wasn't entitled to view it until closing. Being asked to commit to a legally binding agreement without seeing the home warranty was like boarding a plane without knowing the safety protocols.</p>\n<p><strong>Red Flag #2: HOA misrepresentations.</strong></p>\n<p>During our November 12 meeting, Trish assured me there were no restrictions on security cameras — any issues would fall under city bylaws. She confirmed no restrictions on fire pits unless there was a fire ban. She said the fence height restriction was the primary HOA concern, and there was nothing else I needed to be aware of. Colton noted in a contemporaneous recording (Nov 20, 2024) that Trish had told him \"the restricted cabinet for the HOA dissolves when I purchase the property\" — a claim that is factually incorrect under Melcor's continuing architectural control guidelines. /* R2-Q3: Colton's on-record account, Nov 20 2024 DocuSign recording */ These assurances would prove to be incomplete at best.</p>\n<p><strong>Red Flag #3: My name was wrong on legal documents.</strong></p>\n<p>Trish repeatedly misspelled my name on the legal documents and refused to correct it. When I pressed the issue, I was told that changing my name on the documents now would be \"extra work\" and that they would handle it with a future change request — presumably at additional cost. On a $600,000+ purchase. My name.</p>\n<p><strong>Red Flag #4: DocuSign from a personal email.</strong></p>\n<p>The emails and documents came from a personal email address, not a Douglas Homes corporate account. The contract was e-signed by \"DW\" through a numbered Alberta corporation's DocuSign — not Douglas Homes' own system. This raised immediate questions about the legitimacy and security of the transaction.</p>\n<p><strong>Red Flag #5: The bathtub specification.</strong></p>\n<p>My Schedule A specified a <strong><a href=\"https://www.hytec.ca/product-detail/AC759?skuid=AC759-0\">Fiberglass Hytec AC759-O</a></strong> bathtub. After reviewing the specs, its near-full-height dimensions were a critical requirement for me. Colton later described in a recorded account how Trish counted tiles on the blueprint rather than consulting the Hytec spec sheet, concluding the tub was \"seven feet.\" /* R2-Q2: Colton's on-record account, Nov 20 2024 DocuSign recording */ This detail would become important as the deal unravelled.</p>\n<p><strong>Red Flag #6: The 8-inch plot plan discrepancy.</strong></p>\n<p>The most critical issue was that the spec home was built <strong>eight inches narrower</strong> than permitted by the architectural guidelines of Lanark Landing. The discrepancy fell under <strong>Section 3.2.2</strong> of the guidelines, which specified minimum lot widths. I asked Douglas Homes to contact <strong>E2 and Associates</strong>, the architectural committee for Lanark Landing, to obtain a formal waiver as defined by <strong>Section 10</strong> of the guidelines. They refused.</p>\n<p><strong>Upgrades we discussed.</strong></p>\n<p>During the November 12 meeting, we also discussed upgrades: tile in the walk-in closet (around <strong>$720</strong>), a gas line to the back of the house for approximately <strong>$300</strong> placed as close to the end of the deck as allowed, and Cat 6 runs in the flex room, above the fireplace, in the primary bedroom, and two in the basement bedrooms. The appliance package included an electric stove — a gas line was not available except for the furnace. The basement ceiling height was eight feet.</p>\n<p><strong>The collapse.</strong></p>\n<p>Over eight days — from signing on November 12 to the final call on November 18 — every conversation raised new concerns rather than resolving old ones. By November 20, the deal was dead. My deposit was refunded.</p>\n<p>Looking back, I wish I had applied more rigorous due diligence from the start. I wish I had demanded the home warranty and a sample contract before ever putting money down. My earnest appeal to anyone reading this: seek transparency and demand answers. Do not sweep red flags under the rug.</p>\n<p>— Colton English</p>",
  "douglas-homes/2024-11-18-the-8-inch-divide": "<p>I've always believed that buying a home should be one of life's most exciting milestones. When I signed with Douglas Homes on November 12, 2024 for a spec home at <strong>204 Langwell Common SE</strong> in <strong>Lanark Landing</strong> (a Melcor community in Airdrie), I was filled with that optimism. But what unfolded over the next eight days was a cautionary tale about how even the smallest details, when overlooked or mishandled, can unravel everything.</p>\n<p>I put down a <strong>$5,000 bank draft</strong> as my initial deposit. My contact was <strong>Trish Braun</strong>. Her confidence was comforting at first, but that comfort was short-lived.</p>\n<p><strong>The contract and the warranty wall.</strong></p>\n<p>The first crack appeared when I requested a sample purchase contract before signing. I was met with resistance — a reluctance to share details upfront. After signing, Trish told me that Schedule C (Home Warranty) was not attached and that I wasn't entitled to view it until closing. For someone who values clear communication, this was deeply unsettling.</p>\n<p><strong>The 8-inch discrepancy.</strong></p>\n/* R1-Q2: Contract recording, Nov 12 2024, lines 1187-1214 and 1822-1829 */\n<p>The issue that shattered the deal was an eight-inch discrepancy between the architectural guidelines and the as-built dimensions of the home. The spec home was built eight inches narrower than permitted under <strong>Section 3.2.2</strong> of the Lanark Landing architectural guidelines, which specified minimum building widths for the lot size.</p>\n<p>At the November 12 contract-signing meeting, Colton raised this directly. \"All the other Ferny 3s are 20 feet wide,\" he said. Trish replied: \"I have no idea… it could be a typo for all I know.\" Colton confirmed the practical impact: the missing width eliminated what \"was supposed to be a second linen closet.\" (R1-Q2, Contract recording, Nov 12, 2024)</p>\n<p>Eight inches sounds trivial. In homebuilding, where precision defines property boundaries and future modifications, it was a significant deviation.</p>\n<p>I pushed hard for a formal waiver. On November 18, I made four calls:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p><strong>To Trish Braun</strong> — requesting that Douglas Homes pursue a waiver. She refused and said the approval stamp on the plans meant the builder was responsible for ensuring compliance, but that head office wouldn't provide further documentation.<sup><a href=\"#user-content-fn-1\" id=\"user-content-fnref-1\" data-footnote-ref aria-describedby=\"footnote-label\">1</a></sup></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>To Erin at Melcor</strong> — to understand the waiver process. I pointed out that the approval stamp stated the builder was responsible for ensuring the building aligned with all covenants, and that what Douglas Homes was asking for wasn't a waiver as defined by <strong>Section 10</strong> of the architectural guidelines.<sup><a href=\"#user-content-fn-2\" id=\"user-content-fnref-2\" data-footnote-ref aria-describedby=\"footnote-label\">2</a></sup></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>To E2 and Associates</strong> — the architectural committee for Lanark Landing. I explained that the spec home was built eight inches narrower than permitted by the guidelines, and that Douglas Homes didn't want to contact E2 to resolve the issue. The ideal solution would be for Douglas Homes to obtain a waiver for the discrepancy as outlined in Section 10.<sup><a href=\"#user-content-fn-3\" id=\"user-content-fnref-3\" data-footnote-ref aria-describedby=\"footnote-label\">3</a></sup></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Final call with Trish</strong> — In this call, Trish reiterated that head office wouldn't provide further documentation and that my options were to proceed with the purchase or accept a refund of my deposit.<sup><a href=\"#user-content-fn-4\" id=\"user-content-fnref-4\" data-footnote-ref aria-describedby=\"footnote-label\">4</a></sup></p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Other troubling signs.</strong></p>\n<p>Along the way, I discovered misrepresentations about HOA rules and restrictive covenants that were never fully disclosed. The DocuSign came from a personal email address through a numbered Alberta corporation — not Douglas Homes' official system. My legal name was misspelled on the contract, and correcting it was treated as \"extra work.\"</p>\n<p><strong>The collapse.</strong></p>\n<p>After the final conversation on November 18, where Douglas Homes reiterated their refusal to provide any waiver or resolution, the deal collapsed on November 20. What had started as a hopeful step toward homeownership ended abruptly.</p>\n<p>This experience taught me a hard lesson: buying a home demands transparency, respect, and clear communication. It's not about rushing into the flashiest or most convenient option — it's about ensuring your concerns are heard and addressed with honesty.</p>\n<p>To anyone considering Douglas Homes or any builder: insist on clarity. Ask for sample contracts before you commit. Verify every detail. And demand formal resolutions to any discrepancies. Your future home deserves that level of care.</p>\n<p>— Colton English</p>\n<section data-footnotes class=\"footnotes\"><h2 class=\"sr-only\" id=\"footnote-label\">Footnotes</h2>\n<ol>\n<li id=\"user-content-fn-1\">\n<p><a href=\"https://drive.google.com/file/d/1jxEC7VWIkHkLX4MQ4_CzwWFL0v8Gx3us/\">Recording: Final request for plot plan waiver</a> <a href=\"#user-content-fnref-1\" data-footnote-backref=\"\" aria-label=\"Back to reference 1\" class=\"data-footnote-backref\">↩</a></p>\n</li>\n<li id=\"user-content-fn-2\">\n<p><a href=\"https://drive.google.com/file/d/10ozpAVRtNaj76XGGhW6gIkzf_IioBh_l/\">Recording: Conversation with Erin at Melcor</a> <a href=\"#user-content-fnref-2\" data-footnote-backref=\"\" aria-label=\"Back to reference 2\" class=\"data-footnote-backref\">↩</a></p>\n</li>\n<li id=\"user-content-fn-3\">\n<p><a href=\"https://drive.google.com/file/d/1fdr-DEpgIaOIMDnW5JaZTgFwaXDf04nz/\">Recording: Call with E2 and Associates</a> <a href=\"#user-content-fnref-3\" data-footnote-backref=\"\" aria-label=\"Back to reference 3\" class=\"data-footnote-backref\">↩</a></p>\n</li>\n<li id=\"user-content-fn-4\">\n<p><a href=\"https://drive.google.com/file/d/1o39GNlSlIRC_bEWFuBoFllbkfIjU1drk/\">Recording: Conclusion call with Trish</a> <a href=\"#user-content-fnref-4\" data-footnote-backref=\"\" aria-label=\"Back to reference 4\" class=\"data-footnote-backref\">↩</a></p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</section>",
  "douglas-homes/2024-11-20-a-cautionary-tale": "<p>Today, November 20, 2024, my first attempt at buying a new home officially ended. The builder was Douglas Homes. The property was <strong>204 Langwell Common SE</strong> in <strong>Lanark Landing</strong>, a Melcor community in Airdrie. The salesperson was <strong>Trish Braun</strong>. I want to tell you what happened, because I hope it helps you avoid the same experience.</p>\n<p><strong>The beginning.</strong></p>\n<p>I signed the purchase agreement on November 12 and put down a <strong>$5,000 bank draft</strong>. The home was a spec build — Phase 4, Block 13, Lot 1 of Lanark Landing. My Schedule A specified a <strong><a href=\"https://www.hytec.ca/product-detail/AC759?skuid=AC759-0\">Fiberglass Hytec AC759-O</a></strong> bathtub, whose near-full-height dimensions were a critical requirement. We discussed upgrades including tile in the walk-in closet (around <strong>$720</strong>), a gas line to the back of the house (approximately <strong>$300</strong>), Cat 6 ethernet runs on the main floor and in the basement, and an eight-foot basement ceiling height.</p>\n<p><strong>The red flags I ignored.</strong></p>\n<p>Right from the start, Trish refused to provide a sample contract before signing. After signing, she told me Schedule C (Home Warranty) was not attached and I wasn't entitled to view it until closing. Colton noted in a same-day recording that the DocuSign invitation \"goes to a random numbered Corporation.\" When he raised this with office staff, they replied: \"That's a really good question. I don't know that I have the answer.\" /* R2-Q1: DocuSign recording, Nov 20 2024 */ The contract documents came from a personal email address, e-signed by \"DW\" through a numbered corporation's DocuSign — not Douglas Homes' own system.</p>\n<p><strong>Misrepresentations and the name game.</strong></p>\n<p>After signing, I discovered that the HOA rules and restrictive covenants were not what Trish had represented during our meeting. Colton noted in a contemporaneous recording (Nov 20, 2024) that Trish had told him \"the restricted cabinet for the HOA dissolves when I purchase the property\" — a claim that is factually incorrect under Melcor's continuing architectural control guidelines. /* R2-Q3: DocuSign recording, Nov 20 2024 */ On top of that, in the same recording, Colton described a name discrepancy: \"That signature is with Colton English, the contract's with Colton Wade.\" He noted that rather than reissuing the contract, Trish suggested he \"sign it with the wrong name and then reissue.\" /* R2-Q4: DocuSign recording, Nov 20 2024 */</p>\n<p><strong>The 8-inch discrepancy.</strong></p>\n<p>The deal-breaking issue was an eight-inch discrepancy between the as-built home and the minimum building width under <strong>Section 3.2.2</strong> of the Lanark Landing architectural guidelines. I asked Douglas Homes to obtain a formal waiver from <strong>E2 and Associates</strong> (the architectural committee) under <strong>Section 10</strong> of the guidelines. They refused.</p>\n<p><strong>The final call.</strong></p>\n<p>On November 18, I had a final phone call with Trish. I opened the call by stating: <strong>\"This is a recorded phone call.\"</strong><sup><a href=\"#user-content-fn-1\" id=\"user-content-fnref-1\" data-footnote-ref aria-describedby=\"footnote-label\">1</a></sup> Trish's response to the recording was straightforward — she didn't object. But her position was clear:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>\"In speaking with the management group at head office, there's nothing more they can provide as it relates to this… it's up to your comfort level, if you're comfortable going ahead. Otherwise, they can certainly refund your deposit.\"</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>And then:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>\"There's not gonna be any more discussions about my DocuSign and the e-mail that it came from, or any more discussions on the plotting of the house on the lot. It is what it is.\"</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>\"It is what it is.\"</strong> On a $600,000+ home purchase. On questions about the legitimacy of the signing process and the compliance of the plot plan. That was the answer.</p>\n<p><strong>Why I'm sharing this.</strong></p>\n<p>When you're trading 30 years of your life for a home, you expect a certain level of respect and professionalism. You expect to feel like a valued partner in the process, not a nuisance. My experience with Douglas Homes was the opposite. The deposit was refunded, and I moved on. But the lesson stayed: demand transparency, document everything, and never let a builder tell you that your concerns about a legal agreement are simply \"what it is.\"</p>\n<p>Stay informed, stay cautious, and good luck on your home buying journey.</p>\n<p>— Colton English</p>\n<section data-footnotes class=\"footnotes\"><h2 class=\"sr-only\" id=\"footnote-label\">Footnotes</h2>\n<ol>\n<li id=\"user-content-fn-1\">\n<p><a href=\"https://drive.google.com/file/d/1WPC1CKvAQ1dBWkKSnx8mIjgim5tLdb6_/\">Recording: November 12 meeting with Trish</a> <a href=\"#user-content-fnref-1\" data-footnote-backref=\"\" aria-label=\"Back to reference 1\" class=\"data-footnote-backref\">↩</a></p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</section>",
  "house/2024-11-01-introduction": "<p>Welcome. I'm Colton English, and this is the story of my journey buying a new home.</p>\n<p>For me, buying a house isn't just a financial transaction — it's a 30-year commitment. It's an exchange of a significant portion of my life for a place of comfort, safety, and security. This blog is my way of documenting that journey honestly: the highs and lows, the good builders and the bad ones, the contracts that fell apart and the one that finally worked.</p>\n<p>My journey began in late 2024, without a blueprint (pun intended). All I knew was that I wanted a space of my own — one crafted to my needs, one I could look at years from now as a testament to perseverance and hard-won lessons.</p>\n<p>In the beginning, my view of home-building was romantic. Picking paint colours, choosing fixtures, imagining how the light would fall in the living room. As I embarked on this path, that rosy vision was replaced by the gritty reality of managing contracts, navigating deposits, chasing down specifications, and learning building codes complex enough to make your head spin.</p>\n<p>Yet I wouldn't trade this journey for anything. The bumps along the way — and there were many — eventually helped me navigate the new home building terrain with growing confidence. Today, as I sit in my home, I can see how each hurdle shaped my understanding of this process.</p>\n<p>In this blog, I'll share the stages of my journey: selecting the right builder, managing your budget, dealing with contract disputes, and ultimately, taking possession of a newly built home. All with the intent of equipping you — potential new home buyers and builder researchers — with real, lived experience rather than marketing copy.</p>\n<p>I hope in reading my story you'll find solace that you're not alone in this daunting, yet ultimately rewarding, undertaking. I hope that with each post, you discover something that helps ease your worries or clear your confusion.</p>\n<p>This blog is my journey home. I hope it provides a map for yours.</p>\n<p>Sincerely,\nColton English.</p>",
  "house/2025-07-26-conclusion": "<p>This is the final post in my home-buying journey series. I'm writing this from Langley Terrace SE in Airdrie — the Sterling Homes \"Luna\" that I took possession of on June 2, 2025 — and I want to look back at the trail I traveled to get here.</p>\n<p>My path to homeownership ran through three builders over about seven months:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Douglas Homes</strong> (November 2024) — I signed a contract for a spec home at 204 Langwell Common SE in Lanark Landing, a Melcor community in Airdrie. I put down a $5,000 bank draft. Over eight days, I discovered an 8-inch plot plan discrepancy, a refusal to provide the home warranty before closing, and a salesperson who sent contracts from a personal email through a numbered corporation's DocuSign. The deal collapsed on November 20 when Douglas Homes refused to seek a formal waiver under Section 10 of the architectural guidelines and offered to refund my deposit instead.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Jayman Built</strong> (March–May 2025) — I received a purchase agreement on March 4, 2025 for an Avid 20 with revised ensuite at 71 Legacy Reach Court SE in Calgary's Legacy community. I paid $7,820 for the revised ensuite and $12,600 for the Fit and Finish Extra package. Their brochure promised \"80\" height, chrome frame, 10 mil glass shower door\" — but the contract was vague, and when I asked for clarification, the specs kept shrinking: first to 70\"/5mil, then 75\"/6mil. After 16 days of silence from the sales manager and a formal dispute letter to the VP, Jayman terminated the agreement in early May.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Sterling Homes</strong> (May–June 2025) — My first contact was Jason Tang, and the difference was immediate. No sales pressure, straight answers. The purchase agreement was comprehensive, every schedule was present, and the home warranty was included as a matter of course. CIBC approved my mortgage on May 21. The home inspection on May 28 with Marty Keough from Nook &#x26; Cranny came back clean. I took possession on June 2.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Here's what I learned.</p>\n<p><strong>Lesson One: Demand the contract before you sign anything.</strong></p>\n<p>Douglas Homes refused to provide a sample contract or the home warranty (Schedule C) before closing. That's not standard practice — it's a red flag. If a builder won't let you review the full agreement and all schedules before you put money down, walk away.</p>\n<p><strong>Lesson Two: The brochure is not the contract.</strong></p>\n<p>Jayman's glossy Fit and Finish brochure described an 80\" shower with 10mil glass. The contract referenced \"other shower stalls applicable to plan\" without specifying dimensions or materials. When there's a gap between what's advertised and what's written, the written contract governs — and builders know this. Get every specification that matters to you written into the agreement explicitly.</p>\n<p><strong>Lesson Three: Record everything.</strong></p>\n<p>I recorded phone calls (with notice), saved every email, and documented every conversation. When Douglas Homes told me to \"just trust them,\" the recordings told a different story. When Jayman's specs changed between April 10 and April 11, the emails were the evidence. Documentation isn't paranoia — it's due diligence.</p>\n<p><strong>Lesson Four: A quick-possession home can be the right move.</strong></p>\n<p>After two failed attempts with pre-construction homes, Sterling's quick-possession Luna model meant I could see exactly what I was buying. I was settled into my home before Jayman had even broken ground on the Legacy lot, and long before the Douglas Homes property would have been completed. The home was more affordable and included the features that mattered most to me, including full-height tile in the bathroom — the very detail that was the centre of my dispute with Jayman.</p>\n<p><strong>Lesson Five: The sale is just the beginning.</strong></p>\n<p>Post-possession brought its own challenges: a site supervisor (Mike) who dismissed concerns and provided dangerously wrong information about foam off-gassing, a warranty app (Virtuo) with a critical Android bug, and an eavestrough issue that took weeks to get addressed. The warranty phase tested my patience more than the buying phase. Be prepared to advocate for yourself after the keys are in your hand.</p>\n<p>This journey has been about more than buying a house. It's been about understanding the value of a 30-year commitment — the exchange of time for security, and the importance of finding a builder who respects that. My hope is that by sharing this story, I can help you find a builder who will honour your commitment and help you build a home that is truly worth the exchange.</p>\n<p>— Colton English</p>",
  "jayman-built/2025-03-04-a-tale-of-two-contracts": "<p>After my experience with Douglas Homes collapsed in November 2024, I started looking again. My second attempt at buying a new home was with Jayman Built, and it began with genuine optimism.</p>\n<p><strong>March 4, 2025: The purchase agreement.</strong></p>\n<p>On March 4, 2025, I received the purchase agreement for a home at <strong>71 Legacy Reach Court SE, Calgary, Alberta</strong>, in the community of <strong>Legacy</strong>. The model was an <strong>Avid 20 with revised ensuite</strong> — not the \"Cooper\" that some of their marketing referenced, but the Avid 20 specifically. My sales associate was <strong>Brittney Mack</strong>.</p>\n<p>The agreement included two key line items:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>$7,820</strong> for the \"Revised Ensuite\" — creating a 4-piece ensuite with a separate soaker tub and shower</li>\n<li><strong>$12,600</strong> for \"Fit and Finish Extra (2)\"</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The contract also referenced specifications from the Jayman Built <a href=\"https://www.jayman.com/assets/Uploads/JAY-2609-Fit-and-Finish-Brochure-CAL_WEB_2025.pdf\">Fit and Finish Brochure</a>, which described the ensuite in specific, enticing terms:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>\"4-piece ensuites include curbless tiled shower recessed into the floor sloped towards a 32\" linear drain. Walls are tiled to ceiling. Includes 80\" height, chrome frame, 10 mil glass shower door.\"</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This brochure wasn't a vague marketing flyer — it read like a specification sheet. The shower it described was a significant part of why I chose this home. The floor plan showed a marked 42\" by 48\" ensuite shower in the 4-piece configuration.</p>\n<p><strong>The gap between the brochure and the contract.</strong></p>\n<p>When I read the contract closely, the ensuite shower specification was vague. The luxurious details from the brochure — the 80\" height, the 10mil glass, the chrome frame — were nowhere in the written agreement. The contract's only reference to the shower was a clause about \"other shower stalls applicable to plan,\" taken from Addendum B, page 4, point 3. No dimensions. No materials. No specifics.</p>\n<p>I raised this with Brittney, hoping it was a simple oversight. It wasn't.</p>\n<p><strong>Mid-April: The specs start shrinking.</strong></p>\n<p>On April 10, 2025, Brittney emailed me with what she said the actual specification would be: a <strong>70\" height with 5mil glass</strong>. When I challenged this — pointing to the brochure's explicit 80\"/10mil promise — the spec was revised on April 11 to <strong>75\" height with 6mil glass</strong>. Still not what the brochure promised. And none of these numbers appeared anywhere in the signed contract or its addenda.</p>\n<p>Meanwhile, Jayman insisted that upgrading to the 80\" height and 10mil glass promised in the brochure was a nearly <strong>$7,000 CAD upgrade</strong>. The brochure had described it as a standard feature. The contract was silent on it. And now they wanted $7,000 to deliver what was advertised.</p>\n<p><strong>The silence.</strong></p>\n<p>On April 11, I requested escalation to the sales manager, <strong>Michael Klassen</strong>. Despite multiple follow-up emails on April 16, April 17, and April 26, no contact was initiated by Mr. Klassen. It took a direct email from me on <strong>April 27</strong> — explicitly stating concern over the good faith nature of the 16-day delay — to finally elicit a response later that same day.</p>\n<p>On <strong>April 28, 2025</strong>, I sent a formal dispute letter to <strong>Stephanie Myers</strong>, Vice President of Jayman Built Single Family in Calgary, with copies to <strong>David Hooge</strong> (COO) and <strong>Jay Westman</strong> (Chairman &#x26; CEO). The letter laid out the discrepancy, cited the brochure specifications verbatim, and requested remediation including confirmation of a <strong>Navien NPE 240A tankless water heater</strong> as specified in Addendum B.</p>\n<p>Under the principle of <em>contra proferentem</em> — that ambiguous contract terms should be interpreted against the party that drafted them — I believed my interpretation was reasonable and legally defensible.</p>\n<p><strong>The end.</strong></p>\n<p>In early May, Jayman Built terminated the purchase agreement. The home I had planned at Legacy Reach Court was gone.</p>\n<p>This experience taught me that a brochure is not a contract, and that when a builder leaves the contract intentionally vague, the gap between what's advertised and what's delivered can be enormous. If a specification matters to you, demand it in writing — in the contract itself, not in a glossy PDF.</p>\n<p>— Colton English</p>",
  "jayman-built/2025-04-28-the-shower-and-the-silence": "<p>My experience with Jayman Built came down to a shower — and the silence that followed when I asked them to deliver what they advertised.</p>\n<p>I chose Jayman Built for a home at <strong>71 Legacy Reach Court SE</strong> in Calgary's <strong>Legacy</strong> community. The model was an <strong>Avid 20 with revised ensuite</strong>. The purchase agreement arrived on <strong>March 4, 2025</strong>. I paid <strong>$7,820</strong> for the \"Revised Ensuite\" creating a 4-piece ensuite, and <strong>$12,600</strong> for \"Fit and Finish Extra (2).\"</p>\n<p>Among the features that drew me in, one stood out: the ensuite shower described in Jayman's <a href=\"https://www.jayman.com/assets/Uploads/JAY-2609-Fit-and-Finish-Brochure-CAL_WEB_2025.pdf\">Fit and Finish Brochure</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>\"4-piece ensuites include curbless tiled shower recessed into the floor sloped towards a 32\" linear drain. Walls are tiled to ceiling. Includes 80\" height, chrome frame, 10 mil glass shower door.\"</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This wasn't a vague marketing promise. It read like a specification. The floor plan showed a 42\" by 48\" shower base. This was a significant part of why I chose this home.</p>\n<p><strong>The contract was silent.</strong></p>\n<p>When the contract landed, that specification was nowhere. The only reference to the shower was Addendum B, page 4, point 3: \"other shower stalls applicable to plan.\" No dimensions, no materials, no glass thickness. The brochure was referenced as \"the brochure\" without disclaimers. The ambiguity was a glaring red flag.</p>\n<p><strong>The specs kept shrinking.</strong></p>\n<p>I reached out to my sales associate, <strong>Brittney Mack</strong>, to clarify. On <strong>April 10</strong>, Brittney emailed that the specification would be <strong>70\" height with 5mil glass</strong>. When I challenged this against the brochure's explicit 80\"/10mil, she revised it on <strong>April 11</strong> to <strong>75\" height with 6mil glass</strong>. Still not what was advertised. And none of these specs were documented in the signed contract or its addenda.</p>\n<p>When I cited the brochure, Brittney referenced Addendum B, page 4, point 3 — \"other shower stalls applicable to plan\" — but failed to point to any specific clause or document defining the dimensions or materials.</p>\n<p>Jayman insisted that upgrading to the 80\" height and 10mil glass described in their own brochure was a nearly <strong>$7,000 CAD upgrade</strong>. The brochure described it as standard. The contract was silent. And now they wanted $7,000 to deliver what was advertised.</p>\n<p><strong>The 16-day silence.</strong></p>\n<p>On April 11, I requested escalation to the sales manager, <strong>Michael Klassen</strong>. Despite multiple email follow-ups on <strong>April 16, April 17, and April 26</strong>, no contact was initiated. It took a direct email from me to Mr. Klassen on <strong>April 27</strong>, explicitly stating concern over the good faith nature of the <strong>16-day delay</strong>, to finally elicit a response later that same day.</p>\n<p><strong>The formal dispute.</strong></p>\n<p>On <strong>April 28, 2025</strong>, I sent a formal dispute letter to <strong>Stephanie Myers</strong>, Vice President of Jayman Built Single Family in Calgary, with copies to <strong>David Hooge</strong> (COO) and <strong>Jay Westman</strong> (Chairman &#x26; CEO).</p>\n<p>The letter requested specific remediations including:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Shower dimensions: 42\" x 48\" base, 80\" height from threshold, 10mil clear glass, chrome frame, 8\" D handle</li>\n<li>Written confirmation, via contract amendment, that the home would include the <strong>Navien NPE 240A tankless water heater</strong> as specified in Addendum B, Page 4</li>\n</ul>\n<p>I cited the principle of <em><strong>contra proferentem</strong></em> — that ambiguous contract terms should be interpreted against the party that drafted them. My interpretation was reasonable and legally defensible.</p>\n<p><strong>The termination.</strong></p>\n<p>In early May, Jayman Built terminated the purchase agreement. The home at Legacy Reach Court was gone.</p>\n<p>This story is not just about a shower. It's about the gap between what's advertised and what's delivered, and the silence that fills that gap when you ask for accountability. Jayman's brochure was the bait. The vague contract was the trap. And when I pushed back, the response was weeks of silence followed by termination.</p>\n<p>To anyone considering Jayman Built: look beyond the brochure. Get every specification that matters to you written into the contract itself. Watch for vague language. And if you encounter silence when seeking answers, take it as the answer it is.</p>\n<p>— Colton English</p>",
  "sterling-homes/2025-05-03-a-new-beginning": "<p>After two failed attempts at buying a new home — Douglas Homes in November 2024 and Jayman Built from March to May 2025 — I was running low on optimism. Then I found Sterling Homes, and the difference was immediate.</p>\n<p><strong>The first meeting.</strong></p>\n<p>My first point of contact was <strong>Jason Tang</strong> (<a href=\"mailto:lanark@sterlingcalgary.com\">lanark@sterlingcalgary.com</a>), and there was no sales pressure, no vague hand-waving — just straight answers. After my experience with a salesperson who sent contracts from a personal email and a builder whose brochure specs didn't match the contract, Jason's directness was a relief.</p>\n<p>The home was a <strong>quick-possession \"Luna\" model</strong> at <strong>Langley Terrace SE, Airdrie, AB</strong> (job number J#158004). A quick-possession home meant I could see exactly what I was buying — no more speculation about what \"applicable to plan\" might mean.</p>\n<p><strong>The contract.</strong></p>\n<p>The purchase agreement (<code>158004_-_Sterling_Homes_Purchase_Agreementpd.pdf</code>) was comprehensive and clear. Every schedule was present, every specification was detailed, and there were no glaring omissions or ambiguous clauses. The home warranty — a document I had to fight to even see with Douglas Homes — was included as a matter of course.</p>\n<p><strong>Why it mattered.</strong></p>\n<p>The home at Langley Terrace was more affordable than the property I had considered in Legacy with Jayman. But the benefits didn't stop at the price tag. I was able to get the features that were most important to me, including a full-height tile bathroom — a detail that had been the centre of my dispute with Jayman — and a front garage.</p>\n<p>The quick-possession timeline was a major advantage. I would be settled into my new house before Jayman had even broken ground on the Legacy lot, and long before the Douglas Homes property at 204 Langwell Common SE would have been completed.</p>\n<p><strong>Not perfect, but honest.</strong></p>\n<p>I don't want to paint Sterling Homes as flawless. The post-possession experience would bring its own challenges — a site supervisor whose interpersonal skills didn't match his construction knowledge, a warranty app with critical bugs, and repairs that tested my patience. I'll cover all of that in later posts.</p>\n<p>But the sales process — the part that had gone so badly wrong twice before — was transparent, efficient, and respectful. After months of red flags and broken promises, Sterling Homes felt like a genuine partner in the process rather than an adversary.</p>\n<p>For the first time in my home-buying journey, I felt confident I had made the right choice.</p>\n<p>— Colton English</p>",
  "sterling-homes/2025-06-02-the-unveiled-reality-of-homeownership": "<p>The journey from signing the purchase agreement to holding the keys was remarkably smooth. It was everything that came after that tested me.</p>\n<p><strong>Mortgage: May 21, 2025.</strong></p>\n<p>I was working with two lenders, ATB and CIBC, to ensure I was getting the best possible terms. <strong>Jason Tang</strong> was a model of efficiency — he was in constant communication with my mortgage advisor at CIBC, <strong>Heather Hannah</strong>. On <strong>May 21, 2025</strong>, I received the official approval letter from CIBC. After the contract chaos with Douglas Homes and the specification disputes with Jayman, having the financing locked down felt like crossing a real finish line.</p>\n<p><strong>Home inspection: May 28, 2025.</strong></p>\n<p>I hired <strong>Marty Keough</strong> from <strong>Nook &#x26; Cranny Home Inspections</strong>, a firm with a reputation for thoroughness. The inspection of <strong>Langley Terrace</strong>, conducted on <strong>May 28, 2025</strong>, came back remarkably clean. The list of deficiencies was short and consisted of minor, cosmetic issues that were easily addressed. There were no major structural problems, no plumbing or electrical issues, and no signs of shoddy workmanship.</p>\n<p><strong>Possession day: June 2, 2025.</strong></p>\n<p>June 2, 2025 was possession day. I met <strong>Mike</strong>, the site supervisor, for the walkthrough. At first glance, Mike seemed competent and helpful. The walkthrough itself went smoothly enough. But this was the calm before the storm.</p>\n<p><strong>The first cracks.</strong></p>\n<p>On possession day itself, two incidents set the tone for what was to come.</p>\n<p>First, I noticed that the doors on the stacking washer and dryer were hinged on opposite sides, making it awkward to move clothes from one to the other. When I pointed this out and asked if it could be fixed, as I noted in my post-possession records, Mike's response was to tell me I was wrong for thinking the doors should align. It was an unnecessarily defensive reaction to a simple observation.</p>\n<p>Second — and more seriously — one of the outstanding items on the possession list was the foam insulation for the basement party wall. As I noted in my post-possession records, Mike assured me this would be quick: \"It'll only take about half an hour.\" When the crew arrived, they told me the foam would <strong>off-gas for approximately 24 hours</strong> and that it would be <strong>unsafe to stay in the house during that time</strong>. On possession day. The day I was supposed to move in. I consider Mike's \"half an hour\" estimate not just wrong — but dangerously misleading.</p>\n<p><strong>What's ahead.</strong></p>\n<p>The sales process with Sterling was the best of my three builder experiences. Jason Tang, Heather Hannah, and Marty Keough all did their jobs with professionalism and competence. But the post-possession phase — the warranty claims, the Virtuo app, the ongoing repairs, and Mike — would be a different story entirely.</p>\n<p>Becoming a homeowner is a milestone and a journey. The path from contract to keys was smooth. The path from keys to \"this actually feels like home\" is the harder one.</p>\n<p>— Colton English</p>",
  "sterling-homes/2025-06-15-something-about-mike": "<p>Mike was the site supervisor for my Sterling Homes property at Langley Terrace. His construction knowledge was solid. His interpersonal skills were another story. As I documented in my post-possession notes, a pattern emerged over my first weeks as a homeowner: Mike dismissed concerns, overrode colleagues, and — in one case — provided dangerously wrong safety information.</p>\n<p><strong>Incident 1: The dryer door.</strong></p>\n<p>On possession day, June 2, 2025, I noticed that the doors on the stacking washer and dryer were hinged on opposite sides, making it awkward to transfer clothes between them. I pointed this out and asked if it could be fixed before moving in. As I noted in my post-possession records, instead of acknowledging the inconvenience or simply explaining that it wasn't possible, Mike's response was to tell me I was wrong for thinking the doors should align. I found this to be a bizarre and unnecessarily defensive reaction to a straightforward observation.</p>\n<p><strong>Incident 2: The foam off-gassing (safety incident).</strong></p>\n<p>This one is serious. One of the outstanding items on the possession list was the foam insulation for the basement party wall. This was supposed to be completed before I moved in, but it was delayed until possession day.</p>\n<p>As I noted in my post-possession records, Mike assured me it would be quick and painless. <strong>\"It'll only take about half an hour,\"</strong> he said.</p>\n<p>When the spray foam crew arrived, they told me the foam would <strong>off-gas for approximately 24 hours</strong> and that it would be <strong>unsafe to stay in the house during that time</strong>. On possession day. The day I had scheduled my move.</p>\n<p>I consider Mike's \"half an hour\" estimate a safety concern. If I had relied on his assurance and stayed in the house, I would have been exposed to toxic off-gassing fumes. The crew's 24-hour warning directly contradicted Mike's casual dismissal.</p>\n<p><strong>Incident 3: Dismissing a colleague.</strong></p>\n<p>During the walkthrough, <strong>Yaz</strong> — a colleague who was consistently professional and helpful — pointed out a dark spot on the ceiling, a clear, visible water stain. As I observed during the walkthrough, before she could even finish her sentence, Mike talked over her, dismissing it as a shadow or a trick of the light. Yaz was doing her job. From what I witnessed, Mike's instinct was to shut her down rather than investigate.</p>\n<p><strong>Incident 4: The cracked plastic.</strong></p>\n<p>A few days after possession, I discovered a small, 3mm piece of cracked plastic on one of the new appliances. The broken piece had been carefully set back in place — which I interpreted as an attempt to hide the defect. As I noted in my post-possession records, when I pointed this out to Mike, his response was not an apology or an offer to replace it, but a shrug.</p>\n<p><strong>The pattern.</strong></p>\n<p>Each incident on its own might seem minor. Together, as documented in my post-possession notes, they reveal a pattern: dismissal of valid concerns, overriding of colleagues, and a default to \"you're wrong\" rather than \"let me look into it.\" I consider the foam off-gassing incident as crossing from frustrating into genuinely dangerous territory.</p>\n<p>When you're making a 30-year commitment, you expect the people you're working with to take it as seriously as you do. As I documented in my post-possession notes, Mike's construction knowledge may be solid, but his dismissive attitude and the dangerously inaccurate safety information about the foam off-gassing made the early days of homeownership far more stressful than they needed to be.</p>\n<p>— Colton English</p>",
  "sterling-homes/2025-06-20-unfiltered-feedback": "<p>I want to share some unfiltered feedback about my experience with Sterling Homes. I acknowledge upfront that I've had positive experiences with several members of the team. But the overall post-possession experience has left enough of a bitter taste that I need to lay it all out.</p>\n<p><strong>Mike.</strong></p>\n<p>I've written about Mike separately, but to summarize: as I documented in my post-possession notes, the site supervisor was dismissive and unprofessional. When I raised a concern about the washer and dryer door alignment, Mike dismissed it outright rather than acknowledging the issue. I observed Mike talk over his colleague <strong>Yaz</strong> when she pointed out a visible water stain on the ceiling. As I noted in my post-possession records, Mike provided dangerously wrong information about foam off-gassing on possession day — telling me it would take \"half an hour\" when the crew said <strong>24 hours and that it was unsafe to stay</strong>. A 3mm piece of cracked plastic on an appliance had been carefully set back in place — which I interpreted as an attempt to hide the defect. Mike shrugged it off.</p>\n<p><strong>The Virtuo app.</strong></p>\n<p>Sterling uses an app called <strong>Virtuo</strong> for warranty support and communication. As a tech-savvy person, I was initially excited about this. The reality was different.</p>\n<p>The app had a critical UI bug on my <strong>Google Pixel</strong> phone: the navigation menu rendered <em>underneath</em> the native Android navigation buttons, making it physically impossible to tap the \"task\" icon. This isn't an edge case — Google's Pixel phones have a significant market share. It made core functionality unusable.</p>\n<p>Beyond the bug, the \"Virtuo agents\" on the other end simply never actioned my requests. Days, and then weeks, would go by with no response, no acknowledgement, and no progress. Support inquiries were ignored, tickets were left unresolved for extended periods.</p>\n<p><strong>The eavestrough.</strong></p>\n<p>My initial concerns about the eavestrough were raised on <strong>June 30, 2025</strong>, when I reported improperly sloped gutters leading to persistent pooling of water on the southwest corner.</p>\n<p>On <strong>July 11</strong>, I expressed my frustration to <strong>Jaspreet Gill</strong>, noting a <strong>90-degree joint</strong> that did not appear to be properly cut and jointed, and the potential impact of the poor eavestrough installation with water escaping.</p>\n<p><strong>Don Allary</strong> from <strong>Empire Envelope</strong> — the subcontractor — sent a terse reply: <em>\"We have fix the drainage issue with the eavestrough.\"</em> The issue was far from resolved, but that was the extent of the response.</p>\n<p><strong>The outsourcing problem.</strong></p>\n<p>Sterling outsources portions of their customer service to third-party agencies. The level of intimacy and comfort you naturally expect from direct communication with the builder is lost when interactions are facilitated by an impersonal third party. This outsourcing disrupted the flow of communication and seriously impacted the quality of the post-possession experience.</p>\n<p><strong>Credit where it's due.</strong></p>\n<p>Several other Sterling staff members were transparent and forthcoming. Transparency and honesty are core values of mine, and I appreciated those who embodied them. But the negative aspects — what I experienced as Mike's dismissiveness, the dysfunctional Virtuo app, the eavestrough runaround, and the outsourced customer service — seriously overshadowed those positive moments.</p>\n<p>I hope this feedback serves as a candid wake-up call for Sterling Homes. They have potential and resources, but unless they address these gaps in customer service and professionalism, they risk alienating more homeowners.</p>\n<p>— Colton English</p>",
  "sterling-homes/2025-07-12-warranty-and-repair-review": "<p>I took possession of my Sterling Homes property at <strong>Langley Terrace SE, Airdrie, AB</strong> on <strong>June 2, 2025</strong>. My one-year builder's warranty expires on <strong>June 2, 2026</strong>. This post is a comprehensive accounting of every warranty and repair item I've dealt with — the good, the bad, and the still-outstanding.</p>\n<h2>The Warranty Team</h2>\n<p>Over the past year, I've interacted with the following people on the Sterling Homes warranty side:</p>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Person</th>\n<th>Role</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Aly Derwent</strong></td>\n<td>Customer Response Lead (<a href=\"mailto:warranty@sterlingcalgary.com\">warranty@sterlingcalgary.com</a>)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Adam Pocock</strong></td>\n<td>Customer Relations Coordinator (<a href=\"mailto:adam.pocock@sterlingcalgary.com\">adam.pocock@sterlingcalgary.com</a>)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Deborah Curran</strong></td>\n<td>Warranty Response Representative (<a href=\"mailto:deborah.curran@sterlingcalgary.com\">deborah.curran@sterlingcalgary.com</a>)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Brendan McElroy</strong></td>\n<td>Warranty Technical Lead (<a href=\"mailto:brendan.mcelroy@sterlingcalgary.com\">brendan.mcelroy@sterlingcalgary.com</a>)</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Nick Mintchev</strong></td>\n<td>Warranty Tech (<a href=\"mailto:nmintchev@sterlingcalgary.com\">nmintchev@sterlingcalgary.com</a>)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>Credit where it's due: the warranty team has generally been responsive and organized, even when the underlying issues were slow to resolve. The contrast with what I experienced as a dismissive site supervisor (Mike) during the possession phase is stark.</p>\n<h2>Warranty Items — Chronological</h2>\n<h3>Eavestrough (June 30, 2025 → July 11 → ongoing)</h3>\n<p>Reported improperly sloped eavestroughs leading to persistent pooling of water on the southwest corner on <strong>June 30</strong>. On <strong>July 11</strong>, I flagged a <strong>90-degree joint</strong> that was not properly cut and jointed to <strong>Jaspreet Gill</strong>. <strong>Don Allary</strong> from <strong>Empire Envelope</strong> claimed the drainage issue was fixed. It wasn't. This item remained open and I later sent an email titled \"Urgent: Unresolved Eavestrough Deficiencies.\"</p>\n<h3>Stairwell Window (July 15, 2025)</h3>\n<p>The stairwell window glass was cracked. <strong>Aly Derwent</strong> confirmed the window was scheduled for replacement on <strong>July 15, 2025</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Driveway and Walkway (July 24, 2025)</h3>\n<p><strong>July 24, 2025</strong> marked a significant milestone: the concrete for the driveway and walkway was finally poured. A Virtuo email from July 15 had noted seasonal delays due to heavy rain. Drive/walkway final grading was also tracked as a separate item.</p>\n<h3>Fireplace — Missing Crystals and Not Turning On (August 7, 2025)</h3>\n<p>The fireplace was missing its decorative crystals and wouldn't turn on. Aly Derwent confirmed they were waiting on a part for the fireplace repair. An appointment with <strong>Enercare</strong> was scheduled for <strong>August 7, 2025</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Ceiling Texture Repair — Kitchen (August 18–21, 2025)</h3>\n<p>A ceiling texture repair was needed in the kitchen area, anticipated to be scheduled between <strong>August 18 and August 21, 2025</strong>. This item was also noted on the inspection sheet (<code>158004 - First inspection - Langley Terrace.xlsx</code>).</p>\n<h3>Dryer Door (Possession Day)</h3>\n<p>The dryer door was reversed. As I noted in my post-possession records, Mike was dismissive about it, insisting it was supposed to be that way. Tracked in the Notion database.</p>\n<h3>Foam Basement Party Wall (Possession Day)</h3>\n<p>Foam insulation for the basement party wall was delayed until possession day. As I noted in my post-possession records, Mike claimed it would take 30 minutes. The crew said 24 hours of off-gassing, unsafe to stay. I consider this a safety incident on day one.</p>\n<h3>Additional Tracked Items</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Batten paint</strong> — Open. Complete all batten painting.</li>\n<li><strong>Roof final and cleaning</strong> — Deborah Curran forwarded to Jaspreet for review.</li>\n<li><strong>Loose soffit after high winds</strong> — Sterling Warranty acknowledged; piece appeared to have no screws.</li>\n<li><strong>Front sod</strong> — Pending.</li>\n<li><strong>Front steps to be topped up</strong> — Pending.</li>\n<li><strong>Parging</strong> — Pending.</li>\n<li><strong>Seasonal topsoil</strong> — Pending.</li>\n<li><strong>Texturing repair in hallway</strong> — Pending.</li>\n<li><strong>Illegal dumping / construction waste</strong> — Construction waste from the site across the street was blowing into the yard.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Hot Water Failure (December 2025 → ongoing)</h2>\n<p>In <strong>late December 2025</strong>, the hot water failed. A vendor (Lynx Plumbing) reached out in late January/early February 2026.</p>\n<p><strong>Brendan McElroy</strong> noted: \"In order for us to review the issue, we may need to cut some drywall to inspect the water lines and insulation. The water lines are covered with the 2-year distribution warranty.\"</p>\n<p><strong>Adam Pocock</strong> confirmed: \"Lynx Plumbing will attend your upcoming year-end inspection to locate and address the cause of the problem.\"</p>\n<h2>Year-End Inspection</h2>\n<p>On <strong>April 1, 2026</strong>, <strong>Deborah Curran</strong> emailed: \"Your one-year builder's warranty with Sterling Homes concludes on June 2nd.\" She offered a year-end inspection: <strong>\"Would May 26th @ 9:00am work for you for Nick to come over?\"</strong></p>\n<p>The year-end inspection on <strong>May 26, 2026</strong> will include <strong>Nick Mintchev</strong> and the Lynx Plumbing investigation into the hot water issue. The warranty expires on <strong>June 2, 2026</strong>.</p>\n<h2>The Big Picture</h2>\n<p>The initial purchase was smooth — much of this was down to Sterling's excellent communication on financing, concierge services, and possession documents. The construction quality was generally good, and the seasonal work (driveway, grading, landscaping) has improved the curb appeal significantly.</p>\n<p>The warranty phase, though, has been a test of patience. Between the Virtuo app's dysfunction, the eavestrough runaround, the fireplace delay, and the hot water failure, staying on top of every item has been a part-time job. Keep records. Document everything. And don't let survey fatigue stop you from flagging issues.</p>\n<p>Here's to making houses into homes.</p>\n<p>— Colton English</p>",
};
